# Tourbillon Persistent Rules

## Comments
- Limit inline comments to only what is necessary. Aim for 1-3 per file (1 to 2 is good) unless the user explicitly asks for more or the logic is genuinely complex.
- Add a brief (1-3 line) header comment at the top of every file or major class (for example, React component, service, controller) describing its purpose.

## Design Principles
- Apply SOLID principles in new or refactored code.
- When highlighting notable logic or UX features, mention the relevant SOLID principles first.
- Follow DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself): Avoid duplicated logic; extract repeated code into functions, services, helpers, or components.
- Follow KISS (Keep It Simple, Stupid): Prefer the simplest solution that works; avoid overengineering or unnecessary abstractions.
- Follow YAGNI (You Aren't Gonna Need It): Don't write features or abstractions "just in case"; implement things only when required.
- Follow Separation of Concerns (SoC): Each module should handle one responsibility area (very useful for React components, Python modules, .NET services).

## Scraping / Backend Tasks
- When providing scrape commands, include all target collections for the brand in a single command with `timeout /t 5 /nobreak` pauses between each collection call. dont need to generate scraping test cmd with small watches like curl -X POST "http://localhost:5248/api/admin/scrape-brand-official?brand=Jaeger-LeCoultre&collection=Reverso&maxWatches=2", because we can clear watches with brand id if new batch of watches have problems.
- Have to make sure the product card in all watches have clickable brand collections name, and product detailed page, if its not found then proceed for clarifications.
- Refer to @SCRAPING_GUIDE.MD for each brand's product numbers, @backend\data\collections.csv and brands.csv for ID and collections names.
- Do your best to make the scrape consistent produce good products, can follow how you did with patek.
- Scrape full collection sizes; no need for reduced/test counts because problematic data can be wiped by brand ID later.
- For product detailed page web elements, follow patek and vacheron's details, if the page have warranty or inquire, etc... exclude that, only watches specs is needed, each brand website will show the specs in different way, some is more detailed, get the much of it, as long they are in the same structure design, it makes my database diverse, watches from this brand shows different specs settings comparing to others, which I think it is good.

## Naming & Assets
- Watch image filenames follow `brand+model.png` (e.g., `PP6119G.png`).
- Collection images use the collection name (e.g., `reverso.png`).
- Brand images use the brand name (e.g., `patekphilipe.png`).

## Documentation & Config Files
- Add or adjust scraping selectors in `backend/Configuration/brand-configs.json` and capture raw HTML snippets in `backend/Pending_Brands_Config.md`.
- Mention these files in summaries whenever they are used so future contributors stay aligned.

## Communication
- Default to concise, professional language.
- Call out open assumptions or follow-up questions explicitly.
- When my implementation idea matches something that already exists in industry practice (design pattern, framework feature, library, or common architecture), teach me the standard approach and then adapt it to my current project structure and tech stack, with concrete code examples.